text:
Buckle up: Happy $TSLA earnings day. Here are my 5 focus areas ranked by importance:

1) Timing of new vehicle ramp. Commentary related on when to expect ramping of new models that will be announced at the October event. Last quarter Elon expected these new models to ‚Äústart of production in the second half of 2025.‚Äù The reason why this is the most important topic is these new models will both accelerate delivery growth and pave the way for higher margin FSD and fleet revenue. 

Side note: currently, the Street is expecting for around 15% delivery growth in CY25. This number will be dramatically impacted by the timing of the ramp of these new models. I suspect by 2026 at least one model will be ramping which should yield delivery growth in CY26 of +20%.

2) Incremental FSD miles driven. This number is going to skyrocket given V12, which came out in March. By April 23, V12 had logged over 300m miles. Extrapolating that for the balance of the June quarter suggests they added around 950m miles, which would imply 95% q/q growth, compared to 19% q/q in Dec-23. Separately, on April 5, Elon posted that it ‚Äúwon‚Äôt be long until Tesla exceeds 10B miles of FSD.‚Äù

3) Auto gross margins ex credits. Historically, this metric has been the focal point of Tesla‚Äôs earnings. This quarter it drops to the 3rd most important factor given near-term profitability is less important than the long-term profitability once new models and FSD ramp in 2026 and beyond. While its importance is diminished on this earnings, it‚Äôs still important. FactSet reports consensus at 16.9% compared to 16.4% in Mar-24. I believe any number above 16% will satisfy investors. In other words, as long as margins hang in there, the story is intact.

5) China. China accounts for about 30% of total vehicle revenue and has been under slight competitive pressures, as evidenced by Market share of Tesla vehicles in China decreasing from 2.3 to 2.2% from the December quarter to March quarter. Last quarter, the takeaway from the China business was Elon‚Äôs confidence for FSD approval. I‚Äôm most interested in any progress in the relationship with Baidu and FSD given advancements in that partnership increase the probability that Tesla will have autonomous success in China down the road.

6) Politics. Musk‚Äôs recent endorsement of Trump and commitment to donate $45m/mo to his campaign poses two new questions around the Tesla story. First, what is he hoping to achieve with a closer relationship with a Trump White House (somehow maintaining of EV tax credits, more favorable legislation related to autonomy)? Second, is Musk entertaining political ambitions in the form of a presidential appointment or potentially greater political ambitions? This of course will be viewed as negative to investors as it would take time away from Tesla. As a reminder, Musk is ineligible for US presidency given he was born outside of the US. He could run for Congress or more likely governor of Texas. I put the odds at less than 10% that Musk wants a future in politics given the world of politics is filled with red tape that goes against his first principles approach to life.

quotedTweet.text:
1. No of people who pay income tax (pay, not file) is 2% or lower of the population. At most 2%. Even if you include dependents it is very, very comfortably less than 10%.

2. A much larger number of people pay GST, but that is mostly covered by GST council and less by Union Budget. Similarly for state taxes. GST rates have been cut compared to pre-GST equivalent rates.

3. Entry-level income tax payment was again reduced this year as exemption was increased (including on capital gains.) An argument can be made that is keeping up with inflation, but again entry level income tax payment starts in India from 4x the per capita income (in America, it is 1/4th per capita income.)

4. People on Twitter are not representative of Indian public. Like it or not, we have universal adult franchise - I support universal adult franchise by the way. Same dynamic has to be accepted in caste/quote debates.

5. "Middle class" is far, far from the median class of India. It is more like 90 percentile plus. If you have a college degree, have/had a formal job and are spending time on Twitter - you are far from 50 percentile.

6. Logically, such a sliver cannot be the "core" base of any political party that actually wants to win elections though of course given English MSM/SM - this class sets the narrative.

7. Who is left? Farmers and non-salaried small businesses. Latter is being slowly but surely forcibly formalised, former the government tried using its political capital for now. 

8. What about the super-rich? This government raised capital gains rate (LT and ST), STT, dividend taxes - one cannot say that it is in anyway helping the rich.

9. The India story remains supremely positive. Our job as taxpayers must be to focus on spending efficiency. Like, government teachers refusing to accept digital attendance must be loudly opposed while having realistic expectations.

10. Given all of the above, this medium will always allow free play to those who demagogue, pander to anger and resentment. The reality is we live in a fast growing but relatively poor per capita income universal adult franchise democracy. If you hate what you see, wait till you see the alternative.

It is what it is. Be grateful for what you have. Or else live to regret it. Spend time constructively on what can be changed. Mostly, it is incremental stuff.
